  "prompt": "How do cooking soda and baking soda differ?",
  "response": "Actually, cooking soda and baking soda are the same thing. The term \"baking soda\" is more commonly used in the United States, while some regions might refer to it as \"cooking soda.\" \n\nBaking soda is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3), a white powdery substance used in baking as a leavening agent. When combined with acidic ingredients like vinegar, buttermilk, or lemon juice, it produces carbon dioxide gas, which helps baked goods rise and become light and fluffy.\n\nSome key uses include:\n1. Baking breads, cakes, and cookies\n2. As a cleaning agent\n3. Neutralizing odors\n4. Personal care (like toothpaste)\n\nBaking powder is a different product that contains baking soda plus other ingredients like cream of tartar, which provides the acidic component needed for leavening.",
